  <!-- WIRRAL MICROBORE SECTION, UNIQUE -->
  <section class="pf-section" style="background:#f1f5f9;">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="pf-section-label">WIRRAL LOCAL KNOWLEDGE</span>
      <h2 style="text-align:center;">The Wirral Microbore Problem. And Why Most Engineers Get It Wrong.</h2>
      <p class="pf-sub">A significant number of Wirral properties built between 1975 and 1995 have microbore central heating systems using 8mm or 10mm copper pipework. These systems block with sludge faster than standard 15mm and 22mm systems and require a completely different approach to power flushing. Most engineers do not handle them correctly.</p>

      <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr;gap:1.5rem;margin-top:2rem;">

        <div class="pf-card pf-card-left-orange">
          <strong style="display:block;color:var(--navy);font-size:1rem;margin-bottom:0.35rem;">Which Wirral Estates Have Microbore Systems</strong>
          <p style="font-size:0.93rem;color:var(--muted);margin:0;line-height:1.65;">Microbore central heating was installed extensively across Wirral's post-war and 1970s-1990s housing estates. Properties built during this period in Moreton CH46, Bebington CH63, Bromborough CH62, Eastham CH62 and the estates of Prenton CH43 commonly have 8mm or 10mm microbore pipework connecting radiators to the main 22mm circuit. You can identify microbore by the very thin copper pipes running along skirting boards or behind radiators, noticeably thinner than the standard 15mm or 22mm pipework you would see in older or newer properties. If your Wirral property was built between 1975 and 1995 and your heating has always been patchy or slow to heat some rooms, microbore sludge blockage is the most likely cause.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="pf-card pf-card-left-red">
          <strong style="display:block;color:var(--navy);font-size:1rem;margin-bottom:0.35rem;">Why Standard Power Flushing Fails on Microbore</strong>
          <p style="font-size:0.93rem;color:var(--muted);margin:0 0 0.75rem;line-height:1.65;">In a standard 15mm or 22mm system, the power flush machine can directly dislodge and flush sludge from the pipework with high-velocity flow. In an 8mm microbore system, this approach carries a serious risk: chunks of dislodged sludge can block the narrow junction points where microbore connects to the main circuit, creating blockages worse than the original contamination. A standard power flush on microbore without proper pre-treatment is one of the most common power flushing mistakes in Wirral properties. The result is a system that works worse after the flush than before it, and an engineer who does not return your calls.</p>
          <div style="background:#fef2f2;border:1px solid #fecaca;border-radius:var(--radius-sm);padding:0.75rem 1rem;">
            <p style="font-size:0.88rem;color:#7f1d1d;margin:0;font-weight:600;">The correct approach: a dedicated chemical cleanse is circulated through the system for several hours first, breaking sludge down into particles small enough to pass safely through the microbore junctions. Only then is the power flush machine connected. This takes longer but prevents junction blockages.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="pf-card pf-card-left-orange">
          <strong style="display:block;color:var(--navy);font-size:1rem;margin-bottom:0.35rem;">What We Do Differently for Wirral Microbore Systems</strong>
          <p style="font-size:0.93rem;color:var(--muted);margin:0;line-height:1.65;">We carry specialist microbore equipment and the correct lower-velocity power flush settings on every van. When we arrive at a Wirral property with microbore pipework, we add a purpose-formulated microbore dispersant chemical and allow adequate dwell time for it to break down the sludge before connecting the machine. We adjust flow rate and pressure settings for the narrower pipework. We flush each microbore leg individually rather than attempting to flush the whole circuit at once. This approach takes more time but delivers a complete result without the risk of junction blocking. We never rush a microbore flush and we never apply standard technique to a non-standard system.</p>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>


  <!-- SIGNS -->
  <section class="pf-section" style="background:#f8fafc;">
    <div class="container">
      <h2 style="text-align:center;">Signs Your Wirral System Needs a Power Flush</h2>
      <p class="pf-sub">Recognise two or more of these? Call us today. We cover all Wirral CH postcodes and can often attend within 48 hours.</p>
      <div class="pf-signs" style="margin-top:2rem;">
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Radiators cold at the bottom or middle</strong><p>The most reliable sign of sludge build-up on any Wirral system. Magnetite settles at the lowest point of the radiator and prevents hot water circulation. Bleeding does not fix this because it is a flow problem, not an air problem.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Some rooms in your Wirral home never warm up properly</strong><p>On a microbore estate property, partial blockages in the narrow pipes mean some radiators receive very little flow. Rooms that are always cold even when the boiler is working correctly are a classic microbore blockage symptom.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Boiler making banging, kettling or gurgling sounds</strong><p>Indicates debris in the system or localised boiling caused by scale on the heat exchanger. Common in older Birkenhead and Wallasey boilers that have operated without a flush for more than 7 years.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>System taking much longer to warm up than it used to</strong><p>A contaminated Wirral system has reduced heat transfer efficiency. If your home takes 45 to 60 minutes to reach temperature when it used to take 20 to 25 minutes, sludge build-up is the most likely cause.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Black or dark water when bleeding radiators</strong><p>Dark water is magnetite in suspension. If you hold a magnet against the copper pipes near your boiler and it sticks, there is significant magnetite contamination inside. On any Wirral system older than 7 years without an annual inhibitor top-up, this is very common.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Installing a new boiler on your existing Wirral system</strong><p>Worcester Bosch, Vaillant, Ideal and Baxi all require a clean system as a warranty condition. A contaminated Wirral system can damage a new heat exchanger within months. A written power flush report is your evidence of compliance with the warranty requirement.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>TRV or valve bodies seized on older CH43, CH46, CH62 estate properties</strong><p>Magnetite can seize radiator valve bodies on older microbore estate systems. If TRVs no longer operate freely, sludge inside the valve body is the most likely cause. We replace seized valves on the same visit as the flush where required.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Boiler cutting out on cold days or at high demand</strong><p>A partially blocked heat exchanger causes temperature to rise too quickly. The safety thermostat cuts the boiler out. On a Wirral property where the boiler works fine in summer but cuts out repeatedly in January, sludge restriction is the most likely cause.</p></div></div>
      </div>
